<p><a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/white-house-logs-trump-health-fatigue-b2876794.html">President Donald Trump </a>has said that plans for his <a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/trump-washington-dc-triumphal-arch-b2843712.html">controversial Arc de Triomphe-style monument</a> in <a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/donald-trump-lincoln-memorial-reflecting-pool-biden-b2873595.html">Washington, D.C.</a> are “moving forward,” as he bragged about his administration “doing arch.”</p>
<p>The president has continually teased the<a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/bulletin/news/arc-de-trump-washington-dc-b2846797.html"> idea of the massive ceremonial arc</a>, which he claims will be built to commemorate the 250th anniversary of the United States.</p>
<p><a href="https://x.com/atrupar/status/1995954771736305905">Speaking to reporters</a>, Trump said his team has already begun discussing plans for the arch.</p>
<p>"There's a group of people out there that have been very successful and we've already starting talking to them,” he said. “We're doing ballrooms, we're doing arch, we have a thing that's being planned that's gonna be a great tribute to the country, as you know.</p>
<p>“You’ve probably heard about it. The arch that we’re looking at by the bridge, by Arlington."</p>
<figure><img alt="Donald Trump has confirmed that plans for his controversial, Arc de Triomphe-style arch are ‘moving forward’" src="https://static.independent.co.uk/2025/11/05/18/20/GettyImages-2240834155.jpeg?quality=75&amp;width=640&amp;auto=webp" srcset="https://static.independent.co.uk/2025/11/05/18/20/GettyImages-2240834155.jpeg?quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;auto=webp 320w, https://static.independent.co.uk/2025/11/05/18/20/GettyImages-2240834155.jpeg?quality=75&amp;width=640&amp;auto=webp 640w"/><figcaption>Donald Trump has confirmed that plans for his controversial, Arc de Triomphe-style arch are ‘moving forward’ (AFP/Getty)</figcaption></figure>
<p>Sources told <a href="https://www.axios.com/2025/11/05/trump-2-billion-fundraising-binge"><em>Axios</em></a> earlier this month that the huge ceremonial arch, dubbed by critics the “Arc de Trump,” will cost $100 million.</p>
<p>“There's a small arch. A middle arch. A large arch,” the source told <em>Axios</em>. “And he likes the large one, of course, as long as it's big and gold and white.”</p>
<p>The arch resembles the famous <a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/topic/arc-de-triomphe">Arc de Triomphe in Paris</a>, which was constructed by Napoleon Bonaparte in 1806 to commemorate the soldiers who died in the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, when asked about who the Washington D.C. arch was being built for, Trump pointed at himself and said, “me,” according to <a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-new-arch-resembling-arc-de-triomphe/">CBS News</a>.</p>
<figure><img alt="The president’s renovation projects, which include demolishing the East Wing of the White House to build a ballroom, continue to be controversial" src="https://static.independent.co.uk/2025/12/01/14/49/GettyImages-2243854169.jpg?quality=75&amp;width=640&amp;auto=webp" srcset="https://static.independent.co.uk/2025/12/01/14/49/GettyImages-2243854169.jpg?quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;auto=webp 320w, https://static.independent.co.uk/2025/12/01/14/49/GettyImages-2243854169.jpg?quality=75&amp;width=640&amp;auto=webp 640w"/><figcaption>The president’s renovation projects, which include demolishing the East Wing of the White House to build a ballroom, continue to be controversial (Getty Images)</figcaption></figure>
<p>Critics have slammed Trump’s plans, though, with <a href="https://x.com/LambFaceDeclan/status/1995966508628148253">one X user</a> suggesting that the golden arch will actually be shaped like the McDonald’s logo, a reference to the president’s well-known love of the fast food chain.</p>
<p>Representative Nellie Pou <a href="https://x.com/RepNellie/status/1995969109037908457">shared a screenshot of a headline</a> claiming that Trump would focus more on “affordability.” She contrasted it with a video of the president talking about his golden arch.</p>
<p>“Again, I’m asking if there is an update on this?” she jabbed.</p>
<p>Trump’s renovation projects have <a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-melania-upset-east-wing-demolition-b2862932.html">remained controversial</a>, with the president reportedly telling construction crews working on his <a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-white-house-ballroom-size-architect-b2873103.html">$350 million ballroom</a> to ignore permitting, zoning, and code requirements.</p>
<figure><img alt="Trump has reportedly told zoning crews to ignore permitting and code requirements" src="https://static.independent.co.uk/2025/11/18/23/53/SEI271405294.jpeg?quality=75&amp;width=640&amp;auto=webp" srcset="https://static.independent.co.uk/2025/11/18/23/53/SEI271405294.jpeg?quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;auto=webp 320w, https://static.independent.co.uk/2025/11/18/23/53/SEI271405294.jpeg?quality=75&amp;width=640&amp;auto=webp 640w"/><figcaption>Trump has reportedly told zoning crews to ignore permitting and code requirements (Reuters)</figcaption></figure>
<p>According to <a data-affiliate="true" href="http://go.redirectingat.com/?id=44681X1458326&amp;articleId=b2877016&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2025%2F11%2F29%2Fus%2Fpolitics%2Ftrump-white-house-ballroom.html&amp;sref=/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-donald-washington-dc-arch-b2877016.html"><em>The New York Times,</em></a> the president has already placed loyalists into positions that will allow him to rush through the ballroom plans.</p>
<p>Previously, he has discussed not needing to follow conventional rules for White House construction, including the <a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/michelle-obama-trump-ballroom-white-house-b2872888.html">demolition of the East Wing</a>.</p>
<p>“I said, ‘How long will it take?’ They said, ‘Sir, you can start tonight… You have zero zoning conditions, you’re the president,’” Trump told a room of potential donors to his ballroom fund.</p>
<p>“You mean I can actually do something I really want?” he continued. “Because I’m used to sitting with heads of community boards and politicians.”</p>
